John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, with this trend pursued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results in exams, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community initiatives.
With more than 30,000 students spread across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to achieve the best level of service for both students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for deepening their studies and access to universities, as well as for the career they have chosen and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an educational sector capable of conceiving and implementing a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and sought after topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If we speak to a man in a language he understands, we can get into his mind.
If we speak to him in his own language, we can enter his heart.”
This quote reminds us well that we can not only rely on English when we intend to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of this year’s recent exams, we found that languages are at the top of the table, with the highest rates of use of independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages reached the highest rating of A.
These data, collected in the 74 schools under the SCIS ranking, show that 72% of students obtained the maximum A score in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A score.
This shows that Scottish independent schools are favouring foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly serve children and young people in the future.
Languages, as an option, are now viewed in the same way as STEM themes (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and not only.
A survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 concluded that, among the reasons for employers’ difficulty filling vacancies, 17 per cent were concerned with lack of language skills.
Therefore, knowing other languages is increasingly an imperative to prepare the young generation for their future careers.
With more potential job opportunities requiring language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career chosen, if you have learned a second language, you will have a tangible advantage in the future with a life-skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, with French being the only language spoken by a two-digit proportion, 15%.
Therefore, investing now in language teaching is important for today’s children.
The proficiency of several languages, particularly those of developing countries, will give children with a better chance of finding relevant employment.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Some of them will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be a set of languages to choose from in independent schools, supported by specialized teaching staff in the area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a pedagogical environment that prepares children and gives them the skills necessary for success, whatever the future reserves for them.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalized business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance for the future of the country, so it is necessary to reflect it in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to make this option available with diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
