“However, we do not see any corresponding U.S. response,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States there will be no trust in our national security and in such circumstances there is no way we can proceed to our disarmament first.”
Although Ri has recycled known North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded as it takes gradual steps, his statements appear to be meaningful insofar as they do not line-uply reject unilateral denuclearization, as opposed to Pyongyang’s previous positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit ever held between a U.S. president in office and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump offered security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea has been seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States claims that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and raises the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, opposing to ‘the declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can put us on our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the extension of sanctions is exacerbating our distrust.”
He did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the stakeholder in this issue were South Korea and not the US, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was drastically different from last year’s when he told the UN General Assembly that directing North Korea’s rockets towards U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim “the rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year had threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, filled Kim with praise for his courage to take steps towards disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions would have to proceed until North Korea's denuclearization.
