These cells, which can "see" a protein common to many cancers, are then injected back into the body.
An experimental vaccine is producing promising results in patients with a number of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and their change in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2. These cells are then injected again into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "controls the growth of various types of cancer, including breast, ovarian, lung and also colorectal cancers," explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach that involves removing immune cells from patients and “teaching them” how to attack cancer cells worked in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
