HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% in new cases
China has announced a 14% leap in the number of its citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected in the country, health authorities said.
Approximately 40,000 new cases were reported only in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases come from transmissions through sexual intercourse, which marks a change in relation to the past.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
However, the number of people who contracted HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, Chinese health authorities said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, in terms of annual homologous variation, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
HIV transmission through sexual intercourse is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT community is said to be frequent.
Studies have estimated that, due to the country’s conservative values, 70 to 90% of men who have had sex with other men end up marrying women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases derive from inappropriate sexual protection in these relationships.
The Chinese government has pledged universal access to HIV medication since 2003 as part of an effort to solve the problem.
