The inventor of the World Wide Web intends to create a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, has created a startup that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of this legendary technology character, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee’s open source platform, Solid.
This allows users to decide where their data is stored and who has access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokfully stated that the underlying intention of Inrupt is to "dominate the world".
“We have to do it now,” he said about the startup.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “personal online data warehouse”, or POD.
This may contain contact lists, task lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in one browser and at the same time.
What is unique about the personal online data warehouse is that it is exclusively up to the user to decide who has access to what type of information.
The company calls it “personal empowerment through data.”
Inrupt’s idea, according to company CEO John Bruce, is to provide adequate resources, processes and skills to help make Solid available to everyone.
The company is currently composed of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some internal programmers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology creators around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt’s website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not introducing a total change in which all of his business models are turned backwards from day to day.
"We're not asking them for permission."
In a Medium post on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that “Inrupt’s mission is to create commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new Web created with Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on the neutrality of the Internet.
Even while launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this next era of the Web,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: tribute to the clergyman decorated with the Victoria Cross in the First Great War
The only clergyman of the Church of England to receive the Victoria Cross during the First Great War as a fighter was honored in his hometown after 100 years.
Lieutenant Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann won the award on September 29, 1918 with the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later and never knew he received the highest British military honour.
Her two grandchildren dropped a commemorative plate at a stop in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of them, Michael Vann, claimed that it was "brilliously symbolic" that the plate had been presented exactly 100 years after the fact that gave the award to his grandfather.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion on the crossing of the Saint-Quentin Channel "in a very thick fog and under closed fire of portable weapons and machine guns."
Then, he ran to the line of fire and, "with the greatest courage," led the line forward before attacking a cannon alone and shooting down three troops from the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s acts were “something I know I would never be able to match, but also a lesson of humility.”
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, deposited a crown of flowers after the parade, led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he was "very honored to participate in the parade" and added that "a genuine hero's courage is being demonstrated through the support that will be given by many people."
