New German warship postponed once again
The latest German navy frigate should have entered service in 2014 to replace Cold War time warships, but it will have to wait at least until next year due to systems prone to failures and an exponentially growing cost, according to local media.
The entry to service of "Rheinland-Pfalz," the commanding ship of the newest Baden-Württemberg class frigates, has now been delayed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit quoting a military spokesman.
The vessel should have joined the navy in 2014, but the disturbing problems after delivery undermined the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg class vessels that the Navy ordered in 2007 will replace the aged Bremen class frigates.
It is known that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, as well as a series of anti-aircraft and anti-boarding missiles, as well as some stealing technologies such as reducing radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include extended periods between maintenances, which would allow the latest fregates to be sent on missions with a maximum duration of two years away from the ports of origin.
However, the ongoing delays made that with the state-of-the-art warships, considered as a way for Germany to project power across borders, they will already be outdated when they enter service, Die Zeit reports.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy refused to put it into service, having returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyards in Hamburg.
This was the first time the navy returned a ship to the shipyard after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but the German media cites a series of crucial “hardware and software defects” that would make the warship useless if used on a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly important, as the Baden-Württemberg class ships would be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half the contingent required for the oldest fregates of the Bremen class.
It has also been known that the vessel is excessively heavy, which reduces its performance and limits the navy’s ability to install additional features in the future.
It is believed that the 7000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" has twice the weight of ships of similar classes used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to hardware failures, the price of the entire project, including crew training, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros, an increase from the 2.2 billion initially budgeted.
The problems of the latest frigates have become particularly important in the light of recent warnings that German naval power is weakening.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, leader of the German parliamentary defense committee, acknowledged that the navy is currently running out of ships capable of being used.
The politician said the problem grew exponentially over time as older ships were put out of service without any vessels to replace them.
In the end, he regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class frigates were able to join the navy.
National Trust spy on the secret life of bats
New investigations are being carried out at a property in the Scottish Highlands with the aim of revealing how bats use the landscape to seek food.
The results are expected to make some light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study, conducted by National Trust for Scotland scientists, will follow common and fruit bats, as well as long-eared browns and Daubenton bats in the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations scattered throughout the property to follow the activities of bats along the station.
Mobile studies will also be conducted by NTS staff and volunteers with portable detectors.
Expert analysis of all recordings will evaluate the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviors on a territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, an advisor to the conservation of the NTS nature, expects the results to reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as meadow farming, as well as the best way to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by the construction and development works that affect dorms and scarce habitat.
Wind turbines and lightning also pose a threat, together with fly-killing papers and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to domestic cat attacks.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given your night hunting habits, your ears are more useful than your eyes when it comes to catching prey.
It is by them used a sophisticated echo tracking technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts who regularly conduct studies, inspections in dormitories and sometimes rescues.
It also created the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats, at the Threave property in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
The director of the property, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
“Here in Threave we have an excellent area for bats,” he said.
“We have the old buildings, many veteran trees and all this good habitat.
However, there is still a lot about bats that we don’t know, so the work we’ve done here and in other properties will help us learn more about what they need to bloom.”
He emphasized the importance of checking if there are bats before maintaining the properties, as the unintended destruction of only one maternity dorm can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their dorms.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to participate to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we simply don’t know how their populations are revengeing.”
