Europe wins again after Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team reached the 14.5 points they needed to beat the United States.
U.S. star Phil Mickelson, who has shown to have serious difficulties almost throughout the tournament, threw his starting tee into the water in hole 16, pair 3, giving the victory to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari has shined in all his rounds, becoming 1 of 4 players to get 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament began in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth lost 5&4 to the worst-ranked European team player Thorbjørn Olesen from Denmark.
The world's highest-ranked player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 and 1 to Ian Poulter of England in what may have been his last Ryder Cup participation.
A veteran of eight Ryder Cups, Spanish Sergio Garcia became the most award-winning European of all tournaments with 25.5 career points.
“It’s not my habit of crying, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It was a tough year.
I can't help but thank Thomas for choosing me and believing me.
I'm so happy we've won the cup.
It was all a team effort and I’m happy to have been able to help,” said an emotional Garcia after Europe’s victory.
He passes the word to his fellow countryman Jon Rham who defeated the U.S. golf legend, Tiger Woods, for 2&1 in singles on Sunday.
“It’s impossible to describe the pride I feel for defeating Tiger Woods. I grew up watching him play,” 23-year-old Rahm said.
Woods lost all four games in France and now has a 13-21-3 record at the Ryder Cup.
Unusual statistical values of one of the biggest players of all time with 14 great titles won and only beaten by Jack Nicklaus.
With the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas, and Tony Finau who had a high-caliber performance throughout the tournament, the remaining U.S. team members have fought for reaching the fairway.
U.S. Captain Jim Furyk spoke after his team's disappointing performance. "I'm proud of them. They fought.
Tomorrow, we can put some fear in Europe.
We fought.
Congratulations to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players were excellent.
We will reorganize ourselves and I will collaborate with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup Commission to move forward.
I like many of these 12 players and I am proud to be your captain.
I have to take the hat off the other team.
They were better."
Updated Red Tide Information: Concentrations Decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, a decrease in Red Tide concentrations has been observed in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of lower stain proliferation were identified in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Sea spot stretches about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
The Red Tide was also seen in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations near or off the coast of Pinella County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations off the coast of Sarasota County, bottom to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom to low concentrations off the coast, and bottom to high concentrations off the county.
There are still reports of respiratory irritations in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the past week, there have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwestern Florida region.
